\v 4 \add Iyyov's\add* sonsÂŠ232303 \add regularly\add* held feasts in theirÂŠ232312 homes, and whenever any of them held a feast, he would inviteÂŠ232310 all his brothers and sistersÂŠ232312 to share the meal with him.
\v 5 \add ThenÂŠ232318 once a feastÂŠ232322 was over\add*, Iyyov would send \add for his children\add* and consecrate themâhe got up earlyÂŠ232326 in the morningÂŠ232327 and offered burntÂŠ232329 offerings for each of them, becauseÂŠ232319 Iyyov said, âPerhaps my \add children\add* have sinnedÂŠ232336 and cursed\f + \fr 1:15 \ft Literally âblessedâ but it's possible that the original reading was âcursedâ and that scribes changed it to âblessedâ in order to avoid the uncomfortable concept of a person cursing God. Traditional manuscripts of the Hebrew Bible don't have a marginal notation about this (as they do in the case of 7:20), but LXX uses âáŒÎœÎ”ÎœÎżÎźÎžÎ·ÏÎ±Îœ ÎșÎ±ÎșÎŹâ which can be rendered as âhave thought evil thingsâ and the Peshitta (Syriac) uses âreviledâ. Many other translations also use âcursedâ since this is the kind of change that scribes are known to have made in similar cases.\f* GodÂŠ232339 in theirÂŠ232340 heartsÂŠ232340.â \add âIt was Job's regular habit to\add* \add intercede for his children\add*.
